To create a TikZ LaTeX diagram that represents the region \( M^{\rm I}(i) \) of possible \( t \) for \( i = \bullet \) in regions labeled by \( -1^* \), \( 1^* \), and \( 2^* \), you can use the following code:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.5]
    % Define the positions of the nodes
    \node (minusone) at (-2,0) {$-1^*$};
    \node (one) at (0,0) {$1^*$};
    \node (two) at (2,0) {$2^*$};

    % Draw lines connecting the nodes to represent the region M^I(i)
    \draw[->] (minusone.east) -- (one.west);
    \draw[->] (one.east) -- (two.west);

    % Add labels for the region M^I(i)
    \node[above right] at (1,0.5) {Region $M^{\rm I}(i)$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

This code will generate a simple diagram with three nodes labeled \( -1^* \), \( 1^* \), and \( 2^* \). Lines are drawn from each node to indicate the direction of possible values of \( t \). The label "Region \( M^{\rm I}(i) \)" is placed above the middle node to indicate where the region lies.

You can compile this LaTeX code using a LaTeX editor like Overleaf or TeXShop to see the resulting diagram.

